{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "(i) There are metric currents T ∈ D k (R d) with a compact support, such that C k (T) ∈ F k (K) for some compact K ⊂ R d, however, C k (T) ̸ ∈ F k (spt T).",
    "(ii) If Q ⊂ R d is compact, convex and has non-empty interior, then T ∈ D k (R d) with spt T ⊂ Q is a flat chain if and only if T ∈ F k (Q).Indeed, one implication is obvious and for the other, consider a sequence of normal currentsN i approximating C k T in a compact set K ⊃ Q.",
    "If F is the nearest-point projection to Q, then F # N i is a sequence of normal currents approximating T in the space F k (Q).We leave the details to the reader.In light of the preceding remark, we consider the special case of the conjecture when we only study d-currents supported in the unit cube Q = [0, 1] d. In this case, the conjecture would in particular imply that the mapC -1 d: F d (Q) → D d (Q) is surjective.",
    "When combined with the identification of L 1 (Q) = F d (Q) from Lemma 2.2,stating that this map is surjective is the same as the statement of Conjecture 1.1 from preliminaries.Finally, we shall need to pass between metric and classical currents when considering pushforwards, which is enabled by the following lemma, proof of which follows immediately from the definitions.Lemma 2.6.",
    "Suppose d, n ∈ N. Suppose T is a compactly supported metric k-current in R d and F: R d → R n is smooth and Lipschitz."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "If F is the nearest-point projection to Q, then F # N i is a sequence of normal currents approximating T in the space F k (Q).We leave the details to the reader.In light of the preceding remark, we consider the special case of the conjecture when we only study d-currents supported in the unit cube Q = [0, 1] d. In this case, the conjecture would in particular imply that the mapC -1 d: F d (Q) → D d (Q) is surjective."
